n concerned with the cultural implications of embodiment, arguing to move away from viewing the body as a prediscursive phenomenon to regarding it as an acculturated body. Age studies have extended this view to the embodied experience of ageing, while drawing attention to the ways in which the ageing body, through its materiality and plasticity, restricts the possibilities of (de)constructing subjectivity. These current debates on embodiment find a strong counterpart in literary representation. The contributions to this anthology investigate how and to what extend physical borderline experiences affect literary form.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAgeism. 0aAging Studies. 0aBody and Embodiment. 0aCulture. 0aDeath in literature. 0aDecay. 0aDiseases in literature. 0aGender Studies. 0aGeneral Literature Studies. 0aHealth. 0aLiterary Studies. 0aLiterature. 0aNarration (Rhetoric) 0aNarrative Theory. 0abody. 0acultural studies. 4aAgeism. 4aAging Studies. 4aBody and Embodiment. 4aBody. 4aCultural Studies. 4aCulture. 4aDecay. 4aGender Studies. 4aGeneral Literature Studies. 4aHealth. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aLiterature. 4aNarrative Theory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh  aAgeism.  aAging Studies.  aBody and Embodiment.  aBody.  aCultural Studies.  aCulture.  aDecay.  aGender Studies.  aGeneral Literature Studies.  aHealth.  aLiterary Studies.  aLiterature.  aNarrative Theory.1 aAblett, Sarah J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClass, Monika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGramshammer-Hohl, Dagmar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrewe-Salfeld, Mirjam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGullette, M